co.s:
#### Data governance and access control

The user emphasizes the importance of controlled data imports due to large user base and data quality concerns, preferring a two-stage approach where users submit data to an inbox for central team review. [1](1)[2](2) Access restrictions and role-based permissions are seen as critical for maintaining data quality. [3](3)

#### Mapping and validation capabilities 

Users want granular control over field mappings and updates, with the ability to selectively update specific attributes while preserving existing data. [4](4) The system should provide clear visibility into data types, validation rules, and potential conflicts during import. [5](5)

#### Template reusability and standardization

The ability to save, share and reuse import mappings across the organization is highlighted as valuable for maintaining consistency. [6](6) Users want downloadable templates and automatic mapping suggestions based on previously used formats. [7](7)

#### Visual feedback and workflow

Color coding and visual indicators are desired to clearly distinguish between new, updated, and unchanged data. [8](8) Users want the ability to filter and view recently imported items directly after import completion. [9](9)

Like Leon said, have the possibility. When I want to do it, I can do it. I also think most the consultants like in the first phase of the project will do the import and probably they do know which kind of prompts helps them.
I think it's helpful that it's kind of violet background see where you did something.

I think basically just a visual representation of the fields I selected before with the criteria. And now it says okay, what a badly detected or what it took out of the Excel sheet and tried to make out of it.
I see here it's a bit more specific what it would do so like directly compared to the image to add an update.

Maybe if you iron out those maybe one or two issues and say, okay, can also upload just the application list and tell the system somehow those are just applications, just import them. I think that's easier than the hassle to go to copy paste to the template.

I think it's also easier just to import any access that you have. Maybe if you iron out those maybe one or two issues and say, okay, can also upload just the application list and tell the system somehow those are just applications, just import them.

When I go back to the Excel so maybe I notice that a lot of changes were in the Accountability. So when I open up later maybe the Excel sheet I know that there are. Those are the differences compared to the Excel.
Okay, you import that. It gave me directly the possibility to filter to those 20 just imported. So that would be nice for the picture thingy.

co.s:
#### AI-assisted import experience

- Users appreciate AI making initial suggestions rather than requiring manual prompts, though they want the option to refine AI analysis when needed. [1](1)[2](2)
- The system should clearly indicate what changes AI makes, allowing users to verify and understand automated modifications. [3](3)

#### Import workflow usability

- Users expect to see a preview of imported data and clear indicators of what will be created vs updated in the system. [4](4)[5](5)
- The ability to edit detected values directly in the interface rather than returning to source files is valued. [6](6)

#### Data structure handling

- While mature organizations typically have well-structured data separated by fact sheet type, the system needs to handle various levels of data organization. [7](7)
- Users want flexibility to import both templated and non-templated files while maintaining data accuracy. [8](8)

#### Visual feedback and filtering

- Clear visual indicators showing modified items and recently imported content help users track changes. [9](9)
- The ability to filter and view recently imported items is seen as valuable for verification. [10](10)

title: Interview slot - Marianne Garrido Minutti-20260121_160618-Meeting Recording

q.text: "I like it. It's friendly and it's faster. It's faster than translate the things that the different Excels to the language of Linix to be able to upload it that I'm used to it but it's. This one is really fast"
"The diagram thing is awesome. But I know it's really difficult to technically speaking to be able to perfection that to the point is really reliable."
"I love that you can save the maps. So the next time is super automated."
"I want to see only the ones that are missing factory type or are missing something. So I'm able to drag and drop or using a little bit the functionality of the inventory."
"This one is new. You weren't able to import in one shot different factsheet types."
"it will be awesome if I can directly upload information using this. This is the safe maps using integration to be able to like I connect with GraphQL"
"I will double check harder because I know it's really difficult to interpret an image into text."
"With this one I will think I will go all the way because I know that I check it right here and A equals B and it's going to be imported as is on the inventory."

co.s:
#### AI-powered import functionality

- Users express high confidence in the Excel import functionality with AI mapping, viewing it as reliable and time-saving compared to manual processes. [1](1)
- The diagram import feature, while promising, is perceived as requiring more development to achieve full reliability. [2](2)

#### User experience and interface improvements

- Users appreciate the ability to save mapping templates for recurring imports, though request search functionality to manage multiple templates efficiently. [3](3)
- Several interface enhancements were suggested, including an "import all" button placement and the ability to filter errors when reviewing large datasets. [4](4)

#### Technical capabilities and integration

- Users value the ability to import different fact sheet types simultaneously through the new mapping interface. [5](5)
- There is interest in extending the mapping functionality to work with integrations and GraphQL connections. [6](6)

#### Data validation and control

- Users emphasize the importance of human verification, particularly for diagram imports where AI interpretation accuracy is critical. [7](7)
- The structured mapping approach for Excel imports provides users with greater confidence in data accuracy compared to diagram imports. [8](8)
